(14, 1, 'Blog 1', '<p>Theres no arguing that velocity has made it&rsquo;s way into pitching and is a corner stone of great pitchers. If you don&rsquo;t throw 90+ in this game than the odds aren&rsquo;t in your favor!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The average velo in the majors has jumped over the last 5-10 years pretty consistently and that average is now 93.8 for pitchers. But this has so much more to do with the game than just pitching.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you look at the fastest thrown ball by fielders&hellip;105!!! Aaron Hicks threw the ball 105 from the outfield and put it on the money to gun down Danny Valencia at home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Velocity gives you more time to slow this game down. If you throw the ball 90+ across the infield vs. 80 or even 70, then it allows you more time to read a hop, set your feet, make an accurate throw.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So try to follow this math here for me&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Short Stop throw is anywhere from 120ft-150ft&hellip; lets call it 135ft for simplicity sakes&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Distance to first 90ft&hellip;average home to first time equals 4.2 secs&hellip;sprinting stride length roughly 7-8ft&hellip;that means 1 stride equals .35secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So average exit velo for High School is 85mph&hellip;hit towards the hole which is around 130 feet&hellip;which means it reaches your glove in roughly 1.04 seconds if we forget resistance from grass&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This means 90mph ball reaches first in 1.02sec 80mph ball reaches first in 1.15sec 70mph ball reaches first in 1.31sec</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This isn&rsquo;t even accounting for magnus effect, spin rate, which theoretically a ball thrown at 90mph will have a higher spin rate vs 70mph thrown ball. Which in returns means that the ball will start to lose more velocity and distance as it travels in the air. Meaning that 70 or 80 mph thrown ball may not even reach first base if thrown at the same trajectory as the 90mph ball&hellip;but back to an ideal situation with not resistance</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This means that in a perfect scenario at 90mph you have roughly 2.14 seconds to field the ball cleanly, transfer to throwing hand, and throw a dart to first&hellip;Versus 70mph where you only have 1.85second, a difference of .29 seconds. Which is almost the difference between 1 stride which is the difference between safe or out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So think about the time where you bobbled the ball because you didn&rsquo;t have the arm strength to sit back and grab a good hop. And you threw that over to first at 70mph rather than 90mph and the guy was safe because of it. Arm strength is one of the staples for all great players no matter if you are a pitcher, infielder, catcher, etc. Make sure you are taking care of your arm and gaining mph.</p>\r\n', 'uploads/blog/1645663140_6010nl-HW-Savvy-Black-White.png', NULL, NULL, 1, 0, '2022-02-23 19:39:00', '2022-02-23 19:39:00', NULL),
